cal Background & Timeline\n  | accessdate = 30 December 2018\n  | publisher  = Federated Indians of Graton Rancheria\n  | year   = 2018\n  | ref = {{harvid|Graton Rancheria: Miwok History|2018}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web\n  | url =  https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1894/01/02/106091765.pdf\n  | title =  \"Prayer-book Cross\" Dedicated.\n  | accessdate = 7 February 2019\n  | work  = The New York Times\n  | year   = 1894\n  | ref = {{harvid|NY Times|2019}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web\n  | url =  https://www.tam.ca.gov/richmond-san-rafael-bridge-improvements/\n  | title = Richmond-San Rafael Bridge Improvements\n  | accessdate = 23 December 2019\n  | publisher  = Transportation Authority of Marin\n  | year   = 2019\n  | ref = {{harvid|Transportation Authority Marin County|2018}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web\n  | url =  http://articles.latimes.com/1989-03-05/opinion/op-122_1_sir-francis-drake\n  | title = Stalking Sir Francis\n  | accessdate = 2 February 2019\n  | publisher  = Los Angeles Times\n  | year   = 2019\n  | ref = {{harvid|L.A. Times Shards|2019}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web\n  | url =  https://www.discoveringnovaalbion.org/strait-of-anian\n  | title = What and where was the Strait of Anian?\n  | accessdate = 8 February 2020\n  | publisher  = Drake Navigators Guild\n  | year   = 2019\n  | ref = {{harvid|DNG|2019}}\n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Commons category|New Albion}}\n\n{{California history}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n[[Category:English colonization of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Pre-statehood history of California]]\n[[Category:Exploration of North America]]\n[[Category:Pre-statehood history of Oregon]]\n[[Category:History of California]]\n[[Category:History of the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Francis Drake]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDrake's coastal exploration and claim", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Albion"}
{"title_page": "Steve King (Colorado legislator)", "text_new": "{{For|other people named Steve King|Stephen King (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name=Steve King\n| image name=Colorado-Rep-Steve-King.jpg\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=[[Colorado's 7th Senate district|7th]]\n| term_start=January 2011\n| term_end=January 7, 2015\n| preceded=[[Josh Penry]]\n| succeeded=[[Ray Scott (Colorado politician)|Ray Scott]]\n| state_house2=Colorado\n| state2=Colorado\n| district2=54th\n| term_start2= January 10, 2007\n| term_end2= January 2011\n| preceded2= [[Josh Penry]]\n| succeeded2= [[Ray Scott (Colorado politician)|Ray Scott]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1965|12|12}}\n| birth_place=\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=\n| profession=\n| university=[[Colorado Mesa University|Mesa State College]]\n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n'''Steve King''' (born December 12, 1965) is an American politician who served in the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] in 2006 and served until January 2011. King was elected to the [[Colorado Senate]] in 2010, and was sworn in January 2011. He represented [[Colorado's 7th Senate district|Senate District 7]] which includes [[Mesa County, Colorado|Mesa County]] and part of [[Garfield County, Colorado|Garfield County]]. He did not run for reelection to the State Senate in 2014, so his term ended in January, 2015.<ref>Ballotpedia. [https://ballotpedia.org/Steve_King_(Colorado) Steve King (Colorado)]. Viewed: 2017-01-28.</ref>\n\n==Biography and early career==\n\nKing graduated from [[Colon High School]] in [[Colon, Michigan]] in 1977, and then earned an [[associate's degree]] from [[Mesa State College|Mesa College]] in 1980. After graduation, he worked as a police officer for the [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] Police Department, receiving law enforcement officer certification from the [[Colorado Law Enforcement Training Academy]] in [[Golden, Colorado]].<ref name=\"resume\">{{cite web |url=http://www.votesteveking.com/steveprofilep2.html |title=Steve's Work History |access-date=2008-04-04 |work=Steve King - State House 54 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412032833/http://www.votesteveking.com/steveprofilep2.html |archive-date=2013-04-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nKing was promoted to detective in 1982, and then transferred back to the patrol division in 1986 while finishing an undergraduate degree. From 1987 to 1988, he worked briefly as an investment broker, and received his bachelor's degree in psychology from [[Mesa State College]] in 1988. He returned to the Grand Junction Police Department in 1988 as a field training officer. In 1990, King received the Grand Junction Police Department Medal of Honor for Life Saving. From 1991 to 1993, King served as president of the Grand Junction Police Officer's Association; in 1992, he was vice-president of the City of Grand Junction's Employees Association, and served as its president in 1993.<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n\nKing began training in martial arts in 1977;<ref name=\"kicksit\"/> he is a second degree [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in [[Jeet Kune Do]] and [[Shorin-Ryu]] [[Karate]]. He received a gold medal in karate at the 1993 [[World Police and Fire Games]] and a silver medal at the 1995 games.<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n\nShortly after marrying in 1991,<ref name=\"kicksit\"/> King, with his wife, Daun, founded American National Protective Services, a company providing self-defense instruction to women and incident management and robbery prevention instruction to businesses. He remains the chief operating officer of the company. In 1999, King joined the Mesa County Sheriff's Office as an investigator for the Complex Crimes Unit. From 2000 through 2006, he served as president of the Mesa County Deputy Sheriff's Association.<ref name=\"resume\"/> King still worked part-time with both the Mesa County Sheriff's Office and American National Protective Services during his first term as a legislator.<ref name=\"kicksit\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Day jobs: State rep kicks it in off-time |url=http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20080804/COMMUNITY_NEWS/917475798/1076&parentprofile=-1 |work=Grand Junction Gree Press |date=4 August 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-10 }}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife Daun have three children.\n\n==Colorado House of Representatives==\n\n===2006 election===\n\nIn the 2006 general elections, King defeated Democrat Richard Alward with 62 percent of the popular vote.\n\n===2007 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=King\n|Year=2007\n|Bill Number 1=HB07-1002\n|Bill Number 2=HB07-1076\n|Bill Number 3=HB07-1125\n|Bill Number 4=HB07-1257\n|Bill Number 5=HB07-1343\n|Bill Number 6=HB07-1350\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/66957921E947F41D87257251007B8D0C?Open&file=1002_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/78D9DBFE2ECF34BD87257251007D4D62?Open&file=1076_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D8AC55403F4AA2E387257251007C71D6?Open&file=1125_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/F9E71D7F4C18448087257267007B7DEB?Open&file=1257_eng.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/5664957448C7B55287257291005F8791?Open&file=1343_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/452E5C758A713BAC8725725E00579AD0?Open&file=1350_enr.pdf\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning consent to search an inmate on parole.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning the provision of training to prevent contraband smuggling, and making an appropriation therefore.\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the regulation of certain communal living situations in which services are provided to fewer than four persons with special needs.\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning child abuse involving selling drugs with knowledge that a child is present.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning genetic testing of all felony offenders, and making an appropriation therefor.\n|Bill Title 6=Concerning the creation of a victim address confidentiality program, making an appropriation therefor, and requiring a post-enactment review of the implementation of this act.\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 5=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 6=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n}}\n\nDuring the 2007 legislative session, King served on the House Business Affairs and Labor Committee and the House Judiciary Committee.<ref name=\"cmtes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-26 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\nIn his first legislative session, King introduced a bill, cosponsored by House Speaker [[Andrew Romanoff]] and signed into law by Gov. Ritter, to allow rape or domestic violence victims to use false addresses in public records.<ref name=\"victims\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Victims call fake address key to safety |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5534744 |work=Denver Post |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"confiden\">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Under the dome |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5689930 |work=Denver Post |date=18 April 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> He was also an outspoken proponent of expanding Colorado's \"[[Make My Day State|Make My Day]]\" law to cover businesses,<ref name=\"oks\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House OKs \"make my day\" change |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5229188 |work=Denver Post |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"adv\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=\"Make My Day Better\" advances |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5225717 |work=Denver Post |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> and against legislation which would have ended Colorado's use of the [[death penalty]].<ref name=\"kill\">{{cite news|first=Alan |last=Gathright |title=Lawmakers kill death-penalty bill |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_5491532,00.html |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=18 April 2007 |access-date=2008-04-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226184657/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_5491532,00.html |archive-date=2008-02-26 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"cold\">{{cite news|first=Alan |last=Gathright |author2=Sue Lindsay |title=Critics say cold-case bill a bid to kill death penalty |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/government/article/0,2777,DRMN_23906_5481875,00.html |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=13 April 2007 |access-date=2008-04-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706163551/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/government/article/0,2777,DRMN_23906_5481875,00.html |archive-date=July 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, King was appointed by Gov. Bill Ritter to a 21-member task on handling and use of [[DNA evidence]].<ref name=\"dna\">{{cite news |first=Miles |last=Moffeit |title=Ritter: DNA over discipline |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_6866316 |work=Denver Post |date=12 September 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> The task force recommended legislation, co-sponsored by King in the state house, to require that DNA evidence in capital cases be preserved.<ref name=\"spur\">{{cite news |first=Miles |last=Moffeit |title=DNA bills spur heated testimony |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8631392 |work=Denver Post |date=20 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"myster\">{{cite news |first=Miles |last=Moffeit |title=DMysteriously added phrase changes intent of DNA bill |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8664896 |work=Denver Post |date=22 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> The bill spurred opposition from a number of [[district attorney]]s because of a provision that would require new trials in cases where evidence had been lost by law enforcement.<ref name=\"allies\">{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Harmon |title=DNA bill pits King against usual allies |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/04/10/041108_1A_King_DNA_bill.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=10 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-11 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> After the bill passed and was signed into law, Grand Junction law enforcement officials expressed concern about the storage capacity required to meet the law's evidence preservation requirements, and approached King for assistance.<ref name=\"capacity\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=King's DNA law leads to capacity worries for GJ police evidence storage |url=http://gjfreepress.com/article/20080523/COMMUNITY_NEWS/792799438 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=23 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, King led Republican legislators in a letter to President [[George W. Bush]] prohibiting illegal immigrants from being detained at jails using [[taser]]s.<ref name=\"taser\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Briefs: Kinetic race won't take place in 2008, perhaps ever again |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7334682 |work=Denver Post |date=1 November 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 legislative session===\nIn the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, King sat on the House Judiciary Committee and the House Local Government Committee.<ref name=\"cmte2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-26 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\nKing was a co-chair of a special legislative committee that recommended the censure of Rep. [[Douglas Bruce]] for kicking a photographer;<ref name=\"jointst\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Joint statement from House on Bruce investigation |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7978019 |work=Denver Post |date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> King had called for his suspension from the House,<ref name=\"alone\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Bruce alone in the House |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8022254 |work=Denver Post |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> and voted to require Bruce to apologize for his actions.<ref name=\"tovote\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House to vote on Bruce censure |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8065454 |work=Denver Post |date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2008 session, King sponsored legislation to give universities (specifically, [[Mesa State College]] in his district and [[Colorado State University]]) greater control over their own investment funds,<ref name=\"control\">{{cite news |first=Colleen |last=Slevin |title=Mesa State, CSU ask lawmakers to control investments |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8027414 |work=Denver Post |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"asset\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Mesa State asset bill advances |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/search/content/news/stories/2008/03/13/031408_9B_investments.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> to raise bails for DUI charges in which suspects also commit \"aggravating offenses\",<ref name=\"famil\">{{cite news |first=Lynn |last=Bartels |title=DUI victims' families back bail hike |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/02/victims-families-hold-breath-over-dui-bill/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=2 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"bonds\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=King to seek higher bonds in DUI ases |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/search/content/news/stories/2008/03/06/030708_12b_bond.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=6 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> and to prevent [[child pornography]] from being copied during legal proceedings.<ref name=\"childp\">{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=King's child-porn bill picks up House support |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/05/01/050208_3a_King_bill.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=1 May 2008 |access-date=2008-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503033006/http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/05/01/050208_3a_King_bill.html |archive-date=2008-05-03 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He also sponsored a ballot measure to allow senior citizens to take advantage of [[property tax]] credits even after moving.<ref name=\"approves\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Committee approves King's tax proposal |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/search/content/news/stories/2008/04/02/040308_4b_tax_question.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=2 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> In total, King sponsored 12 House and Senate bills, seven of which were passed into law.<ref name=\"largely\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Lawmakers largely successful with bills |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/06/14/061508_8b_Bill_report.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=14 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-19 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the legislative session, King was named to an interim committee focusing on wildfire and development issues in mountain areas of Colorado.<ref name=\"forestcmte\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=King appointed to forest committee |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/06/11/061208_6b_King_appointment.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=11 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-14 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In October, King called for a legislative audit on enforcement of a state law prohibiting [[sanctuary city]] policies.<ref name=\"auditimm\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Montero |title=State Rep. King wants immigration law audited |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/oct/14/state-rep-king-wants-immigration-law-audited/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}</ref><ref name=\"wantsaud\">{{cite news|first=Gary |last=Harmon |title=King wants state review of compliance with law against immigration sanctuary |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/10/12/101108_3A_King_immigration.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=12 October 2008 |access-date=2008-11-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016121634/http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/10/12/101108_3A_King_immigration.html |archive-date=October 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, King, frustrated with new regulation and with comments made regarding job losses in Colorado's energy industry, called for Gov. Ritter to fire Dave Neslin, the director of the Colorado Oil and Gas Conservation Commission.<ref name=\"replace\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=King asks for replacement of CO |url=http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20081216/COMMUNITY_NEWS/812159977/1006/NONE&parentprofile=1059&title=King%20asks%20for%20replacement%20of%20COGCC%20director |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=16 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"urges\">{{cite news |first=Todd |last=Hartman |title=Lawmaker urges firing of oil, gas conservation official |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/dec/16/lawmaker-urges-firing-of-oil-gas-conservation/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=16 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 election===\nRep. King sought re-election to the Colorado legislature in 2008; he faced no opposition for the Republican nomination<ref name=\"intensify\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=As races intensify, candidates reveal campaign funds |url=http://gjfreepress.com/article/20080428/COMMUNITY_NEWS/448570948 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=28 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-29 }}</ref> and ran unopposed in the general election as well.<ref name=\"noopp\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone  |title=Rep. King to face no opponent at polls |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/06/12/061308_Candidate.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=12 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-14 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"finance\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson  |title=Campaign finance update |url=http://gjfreepress.com/article/20080613/COMMUNITY_NEWS/404419289 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-14 }}</ref>\n\nKing named education and energy issues as his priorities for the next legislative session.<ref name=\"kidsvot\">{{cite news |first=Erin |last=Slilekoks |title=Kids Voting, Oct. 13, 2008 |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/opinion/stories/2008/10/12/101308_14A_kids_voting.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=12 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In contrast to his typical opposition to tax increases, King also supported a local school bond measure in Grand Junction that was on the 2008 ballot.<ref name=\"penry\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Penry, King endorse School District 51 bond issue |url=http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20080911/COMMUNITY_NEWS/809109933/1064&parentprofile=-1 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=11 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-10-30 }}</ref>\n\n===2009 legislative session===\nFor the 2009 legislative session, King was appointed to the House Judiciary Committee and the House Transportation and Energy Committee.<ref name=\"cmte09\">\n{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231125753/http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node%2F92 |archive-date=31 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2009, King continued his active engagement in the legislature by serving as primary sponsor for 13 bills. His major focus included legislation with an emerging focus on increasing government accountability and transparency. In particular, he sponsored two measures: SB09-241 and HB09-1180. SB09-241<ref name=\"SB09241\">{{cite news | title=SB09-241 |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A33C46D1F9F4F2EC87257553007F530D?Open&file=241_enr.pdf|accessdate=10 October 2012 }}</ref>\n(Katie's Law) requires DNA sampling upon arrest for felony offenses, to be expunged if no conviction is obtained, and Rep. King received national recognition when he was awarded the \"Katie's Heroes\" award for his role in passing this legislation. HB09-1180<ref name=\"HB09-1180\">{{cite news |title=HB09-1180 |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/0CCEBB17C7B80D548725753800635131?Open&file=1180_enr.pdf | accessdate=10 Oct 2012 }}</ref> would have provided more Second Amendment personal safety options for Colorado concealed carry permit holders, but it was postponed indefinitely in committee.\n\n===2010 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=King\n|Year=2010\n|Bill Number 1=HB10-1054\n|Bill Number 2=HB10-1136\n|Bill Number 3= HB10-1334\n|Bill Number 4= SB10-079\n|Bill Number 5= SB10-092\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/C93F548942F35723872576A8002A2A41?Open&file=1054_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/E1BF145053E3EA62872576AC00651D78?Open&file=1136_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/6497F94EFEE7652F872576B80066D97B?Open&file=1334_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/2EA9C2A5C1FE6C11872576AA00696FD4?Open&file=079_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/2D5FE3C68F88F2DC872576A80027B78E?Open&file=092_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 4= Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning presenting school safety information at institutions of higher education.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning emergency safety procedures in Kindergarten-through-twelfth-grade schools.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning changes to indecency crimes. \n|Bill Title 4= Concerning authority to offer additional programs at Mesa State College.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning the exemption from federal regulation of certain items related to exercising the right to bear arms.\n}}\nIn 2010, King presented a bill that would have required all schools, kindergarten\u2013twelfth grade, to perform emergency safety drills each academic year, in addition to the normal fire evacuation drills. The emergency safety protocol drills would include lockdown, evacuation and reverse-evacuation, and [[shelter in place]] drills. However, HB10-1136 was assigned to the House Education Committee, where it was postponed indefinitely.\n\n==Colorado Senate 2011-2015==\n\n===2010 Election===\nIn 2010, Rep. King was eligible for re-election to the 54th House seat; however, he instead chose to run for the open Senate seat in District 7. In the general November election, he defeated Democrat [[Claudette Konola]] and Libertarian [[Gilbert Fuller]] with 67% of the vote.<ref name=\"2010 Results\">{{cite news |title=Colorado State Senate Election Results 2012 |url= http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-senate/2010/\n|work=Denver Post |accessdate=10 Oct 2012 }}\n</ref>\n\n===2011 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=King\n|Year=2011\n|Bill Number 1=SB11-027\n|Bill Number 2=SB11-046\n|Bill Number 3=SB11-093\n|Bill Number 4=SB11-098\n|Bill Number 5=SB11-173\n|Bill Number 6=HB11-1080\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/591FE603A91DC2458725780800800F35?Open&file=027_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/894CDD0D7A3C8DF28725780800803B37?Open&file=046_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D186918CCBB6915287257822007BD8FE?Open&file=093_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/709BABFEFC8F2BC68725781C00698989?Open&file=098_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/85763B644B0DC1F68725780800800F8A?Open&file=173_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9820262AD8F68ED08725780800804995?Open&file=1080_enr.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 3=Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 5= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 6= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning the Colorado economic stability fund.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the mandatory post-enactment review by legislative service agencies of the implementation of enacted bills.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the continuation of the interagency task force on drunk driving.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning the phase-out of the property tax on business personal property.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning interoperable communications in schools.\n|Bill Title 6= Concerning the address confidentiality program, and making an appropriation therefor.\n}}\nFor the 2011 legislative session, Senator King focused on a bill that would have phased-out the property tax on business personal property. SB11-098 allowed for future enactment, once the state has reached prosperity levels adequate to deal with the decrease of tax income. The bill was assigned to the Senate State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee, and it was postponed indefinitely on a party-line 3-2 vote.<ref name=\"Open States SB11-098\">{{cite news |title=Open States \u2013 SB11-098|url= http://openstates.org/co/bills/2011A/SB11-098/|\nwork=Open States |accessdate=11 Oct 2012 }}</ref>\n\nKing was appointed to serve on the Senate Transportation, Judiciary, and Legislative Audit Committees for the 68th General Assembly.<ref name=\"CO GA Page\">{{cite news|title=Colorado General Assembly-Steve King|url=http://www.state.co.us/gov_dir/leg_dir/Senate/members/Sen07.htm|work=Colorado General Assembly|access-date=10 Oct 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022153333/http://www.state.co.us/gov_dir/leg_dir/Senate/members/Sen07.htm|archive-date=22 October 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\nSenator King was appointed to the Mental Illness in the Criminal Justice System Interim Committee for the 2011 Interim; this committee focused on maintaining legislative oversight into the continuing examination of persons who are mentally ill in the Colorado Justice System.\nKing was appointed to the Police Officers' and Firefighters' Pension Reform Commission and the Senate Transportation Legislation Review Committee for the 2011 Interim as well.\n\n===2012 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=King\n|Year=2012\n|Bill Number 1=SB12-034\n|Bill Number 2=SB12-079\n|Bill Number 3=SB12-117\n|Bill Number 4=HB12-1004\n|Bill Number 5=HB12-1064\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/493E5830AD3300A487257981007F0D10?Open&file=034_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/F05828BE5B756CE987257981007F34AC?Open&file=079_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/3830B379C5DC1E8487257982007166A1?Open&file=117_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/210803A9B1165F8B87257981007F6946?Open&file=1004_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/E02212357C1248D187257981007F40BA?Open&file=1064_ren.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 2= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely on House calendar\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning repeal of the rapid screen program to identify high-emitting motor vehicles.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning revisions to the Safe2Tell Program relating to advances in communications technology.\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the penalties for person who drive while under the influence of alcohol or drugs.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning requiring local building codes to allow the use of lumber milled from certain trees as building framing material.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning the prohibition of limitations concerning firearms during an official state of emergency. \n}}\nIn 2012, King focused on addressing a number of important issues in Colorado: addressing technological changes for the Safe2Tell program, updating penalties for impaired driving, and focusing on correcting gun limitation laws.<ref name=\"CO Capitol Watch\">{{cite news |title=Colorado General Assembly-Steve King |url=http://www.coloradocapitolwatch.com/bill/1/HB12-1064/2012/0/ |work=Colorado Capitol Watch |accessdate=11 Oct 2012 }}</ref> HB12-1064 would prohibit government and law enforcement from banning possession and use of firearms during a state emergency unless that weapon was being used for a crime. The bill, one of four gun bills proposed during session, passed on a party-line vote in the Republican-controlled House before being sent over to the Democrat-controlled Senate. In the Senate, it was introduced to the Senate State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee and failed to be referred to the Committee of the Whole on a 2-3 party-line vote. \n<ref name=\"Open States HB12-0164\">{{cite news |title=Colorado General Assembly-Steve King|url= http://openstates.org/co/bills/2012A/HB12-1064/|\nwork=Open States |accessdate=11 Oct 2012 }}</ref>\n\nKing maintained his appointments on two Interim Committees for the 2012 off-session as well: the Police Officers' and Firefighters' Pension Reform Commission and the Senate Transportation Legislation Review Committee.\n\n===2013 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=King\n|Year=2013\n|Bill Number 1=\n|Bill Number 2=\n|Bill Number 3=\n|Bill Number 4=\n|Bill Number 5=\n|Bill Link 1=\n|Bill Link 2=\n|Bill Link 3=\n|Bill Link 4=\n|Bill Link 5=\n|Bill Status 1=\n|Bill Status 2=\n|Bill Status 3=\n|Bill Status 4=\n|Bill Status 5=\n|Bill Title 1=\n|Bill Title 2= \n|Bill Title 3=\n|Bill Title 4= \n|Bill Title 5= \n}}\n\n\tKing was appointed to serve on the Senate Judiciary Committee, Transportation Committee, and the Legislative Audit Committee.\n\n==Run for sheriff and criminal indictment and plea==\nWhile still serving as Senator, on June 6, 2014, King was accused by Mesa County Sheriff Stan Hilkey of falsifying timecards King had filed in association with his part-time job with the department. At the time, King was running to replace Hilkey as sheriff, and denied all allegations and initially refused to drop from the race. On July 16, King announced he would be withdrawing from the race due to the impending allegations.<ref>http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_26246364/state-sen-steve-king-charged-three-felonies?source=pkg</ref> On January 23, 2015, King pleaded guilty to embezzlement and official misconduct. He was ordered to pay restitution and serve 2 years probation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/former-colorado-state-senator-steve-king-pleads-guilty-to-embezzlement01232015 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192012/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/former-colorado-state-senator-steve-king-pleads-guilty-to-embezzlement01232015 |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/steve-king-cops-a-plea|title=Steve King cops a plea  {{!}}  GJSentinel.com|last=Shockley|first=Paul|website=www.gjsentinel.com|access-date=2016-05-18|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602032330/http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/steve-king-cops-a-plea|archive-date=2016-06-02|df=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140208023159/http://www.votesteveking.com/ Campaign web site]\n*[http://www.coloradosenatenews.com/?q=content/senator-steve-king Colorado GOP Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121022153333/http://www.state.co.us/gov_dir/leg_dir/Senate/members/Sen07.htm Colorado General Assembly Website]\n\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Steve}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Colorado politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people named Steve King|Stephen King (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder \n| name=Steve King\n| image name=Colorado-Rep-Steve-King.jpg\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=[[Colorado's 7th Senate district|7th]]\n| term_start=January 2011\n| term_end=January 7, 2015\n| preceded=[[Josh Penry]]\n| succeeded=[[Ray Scott (Colorado politician)|Ray Scott]]\n| state_house2=Colorado\n| state2=Colorado\n| district2=54th\n| term_start2= January 10, 2007\n| term_end2= January 2011\n| preceded2= [[Josh Penry]]\n| succeeded2= [[Ray Scott (Colorado politician)|Ray Scott]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1965|12|12}}\n| birth_place=\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=\n| profession=\n| university=[[Colorado Mesa University|Mesa State College]]\n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n'''Steve King''' (born December 12, 1965) is an American politician who served in the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] in 2006 and served until January 2011. King was elected to the [[Colorado Senate]] in 2010, and was sworn in January 2011. He represented [[Colorado's 7th Senate district|Senate District 7]] which includes [[Mesa County, Colorado|Mesa County]] and part of [[Garfield County, Colorado|Garfield County]]. He did not run for reelection to the State Senate in 2014, so his term ended in January, 2015.<ref>Ballotpedia. [https://ballotpedia.org/Steve_King_(Colorado) Steve King (Colorado)]. Viewed: 2017-01-28.</ref>\n\n==Biography and early career==\n\nKing graduated from [[Colon High School]] in [[Colon, Michigan]] in 1977, and then earned an [[associate's degree]] from [[Mesa State College|Mesa College]] in 1980. After graduation, he worked as a police officer for the [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] Police Department, receiving law enforcement officer certification from the [[Colorado Law Enforcement Training Academy]] in [[Golden, Colorado]].<ref name=\"resume\">{{cite web |url=http://www.votesteveking.com/steveprofilep2.html |title=Steve's Work History |access-date=2008-04-04 |work=Steve King - State House 54 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412032833/http://www.votesteveking.com/steveprofilep2.html |archive-date=2013-04-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nKing was promoted to detective in 1982, and then transferred back to the patrol division in 1986 while finishing an undergraduate degree. From 1987 to 1988, he worked briefly as an investment broker, and received his bachelor's degree in psychology from [[Mesa State College]] in 1988. He returned to the Grand Junction Police Department in 1988 as a field training officer. In 1990, King received the Grand Junction Police Department Medal of Honor for Life Saving. From 1991 to 1993, King served as president of the Grand Junction Police Officer's Association; in 1992, he was vice-president of the City of Grand Junction's Employees Association, and served as its president in 1993.<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n\nKing began training in martial arts in 1977;<ref name=\"kicksit\"/> he is a second degree [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in [[Jeet Kune Do]] and [[Shorin-Ryu]] [[Karate]]. He received a gold medal in karate at the 1993 [[World Police and Fire Games]] and a silver medal at the 1995 games.<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n\nShortly after marrying in 1991,<ref name=\"kicksit\"/> King, with his wife, Daun, founded American National Protective Services, a company providing self-defense instruction to women and incident management and robbery prevention instruction to businesses. He remains the chief operating officer of the company. In 1999, King joined the Mesa County Sheriff's Office as an investigator for the Complex Crimes Unit. From 2000 through 2006, he served as president of the Mesa County Deputy Sheriff's Association.<ref name=\"resume\"/> King still worked part-time with both the Mesa County Sheriff's Office and American National Protective Services during his first term as a legislator.<ref name=\"kicksit\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Day jobs: State rep kicks it in off-time |url=http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20080804/COMMUNITY_NEWS/917475798/1076&parentprofile=-1 |work=Grand Junction Gree Press |date=4 August 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-10 }}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife Daun have three children.\n\n==Colorado House of Representatives==\n\n===2006 election===\n\nIn the 2006 general elections, King defeated Democrat Richard Alward with 62 percent of the popular vote.\n\n===2007 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=King\n|Year=2007\n|Bill Number 1=HB07-1002\n|Bill Number 2=HB07-1076\n|Bill Number 3=HB07-1125\n|Bill Number 4=HB07-1257\n|Bill Number 5=HB07-1343\n|Bill Number 6=HB07-1350\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/66957921E947F41D87257251007B8D0C?Open&file=1002_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/78D9DBFE2ECF34BD87257251007D4D62?Open&file=1076_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D8AC55403F4AA2E387257251007C71D6?Open&file=1125_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/F9E71D7F4C18448087257267007B7DEB?Open&file=1257_eng.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/5664957448C7B55287257291005F8791?Open&file=1343_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/452E5C758A713BAC8725725E00579AD0?Open&file=1350_enr.pdf\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning consent to search an inmate on parole.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning the provision of training to prevent contraband smuggling, and making an appropriation therefore.\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the regulation of certain communal living situations in which services are provided to fewer than four persons with special needs.\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning child abuse involving selling drugs with knowledge that a child is present.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning genetic testing of all felony offenders, and making an appropriation therefor.\n|Bill Title 6=Concerning the creation of a victim address confidentiality program, making an appropriation therefor, and requiring a post-enactment review of the implementation of this act.\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 5=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 6=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter|Ritter]]\n}}\n\nDuring the 2007 legislative session, King served on the House Business Affairs and Labor Committee and the House Judiciary Committee.<ref name=\"cmtes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-26 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\nIn his first legislative session, King introduced a bill, cosponsored by House Speaker [[Andrew Romanoff]] and signed into law by Gov. Ritter, to allow rape or domestic violence victims to use false addresses in public records.<ref name=\"victims\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Victims call fake address key to safety |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5534744 |work=Denver Post |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"confiden\">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Under the dome |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5689930 |work=Denver Post |date=18 April 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> He was also an outspoken proponent of expanding Colorado's \"[[Make My Day State|Make My Day]]\" law to cover businesses,<ref name=\"oks\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House OKs \"make my day\" change |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5229188 |work=Denver Post |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"adv\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=\"Make My Day Better\" advances |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5225717 |work=Denver Post |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> and against legislation which would have ended Colorado's use of the [[death penalty]].<ref name=\"kill\">{{cite news|first=Alan |last=Gathright |title=Lawmakers kill death-penalty bill |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_5491532,00.html |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=18 April 2007 |access-date=2008-04-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226184657/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/local/article/0,1299,DRMN_15_5491532,00.html |archive-date=2008-02-26 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"cold\">{{cite news|first=Alan |last=Gathright |author2=Sue Lindsay |title=Critics say cold-case bill a bid to kill death penalty |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/government/article/0,2777,DRMN_23906_5481875,00.html |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=13 April 2007 |access-date=2008-04-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706163551/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/government/article/0,2777,DRMN_23906_5481875,00.html |archive-date=July 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, King was appointed by Gov. Bill Ritter to a 21-member task on handling and use of [[DNA evidence]].<ref name=\"dna\">{{cite news |first=Miles |last=Moffeit |title=Ritter: DNA over discipline |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_6866316 |work=Denver Post |date=12 September 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> The task force recommended legislation, co-sponsored by King in the state house, to require that DNA evidence in capital cases be preserved.<ref name=\"spur\">{{cite news |first=Miles |last=Moffeit |title=DNA bills spur heated testimony |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8631392 |work=Denver Post |date=20 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"myster\">{{cite news |first=Miles |last=Moffeit |title=DMysteriously added phrase changes intent of DNA bill |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8664896 |work=Denver Post |date=22 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> The bill spurred opposition from a number of [[district attorney]]s because of a provision that would require new trials in cases where evidence had been lost by law enforcement.<ref name=\"allies\">{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Harmon |title=DNA bill pits King against usual allies |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/04/10/041108_1A_King_DNA_bill.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=10 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-11 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> After the bill passed and was signed into law, Grand Junction law enforcement officials expressed concern about the storage capacity required to meet the law's evidence preservation requirements, and approached King for assistance.<ref name=\"capacity\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=King's DNA law leads to capacity worries for GJ police evidence storage |url=http://gjfreepress.com/article/20080523/COMMUNITY_NEWS/792799438 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=23 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-13 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, King led Republican legislators in a letter to President [[George W. Bush]] prohibiting illegal immigrants from being detained at jails using [[taser]]s.<ref name=\"taser\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Briefs: Kinetic race won't take place in 2008, perhaps ever again |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7334682 |work=Denver Post |date=1 November 2007 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 legislative session===\nIn the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, King sat on the House Judiciary Committee and the House Local Government Committee.<ref name=\"cmte2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-26 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\nKing was a co-chair of a special legislative committee that recommended the censure of Rep. [[Douglas Bruce]] for kicking a photographer;<ref name=\"jointst\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Joint statement from House on Bruce investigation |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7978019 |work=Denver Post |date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> King had called for his suspension from the House,<ref name=\"alone\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Bruce alone in the House |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8022254 |work=Denver Post |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> and voted to require Bruce to apologize for his actions.<ref name=\"tovote\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House to vote on Bruce censure |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8065454 |work=Denver Post |date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2008 session, King sponsored legislation to give universities (specifically, [[Mesa State College]] in his district and [[Colorado State University]]) greater control over their own investment funds,<ref name=\"control\">{{cite news |first=Colleen |last=Slevin |title=Mesa State, CSU ask lawmakers to control investments |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_8027414 |work=Denver Post |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"asset\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Mesa State asset bill advances |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/search/content/news/stories/2008/03/13/031408_9B_investments.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> to raise bails for DUI charges in which suspects also commit \"aggravating offenses\",<ref name=\"famil\">{{cite news |first=Lynn |last=Bartels |title=DUI victims' families back bail hike |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/02/victims-families-hold-breath-over-dui-bill/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=2 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref><ref name=\"bonds\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=King to seek higher bonds in DUI ases |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/search/content/news/stories/2008/03/06/030708_12b_bond.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=6 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> and to prevent [[child pornography]] from being copied during legal proceedings.<ref name=\"childp\">{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=King's child-porn bill picks up House support |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/05/01/050208_3a_King_bill.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=1 May 2008 |access-date=2008-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503033006/http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/05/01/050208_3a_King_bill.html |archive-date=2008-05-03 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He also sponsored a ballot measure to allow senior citizens to take advantage of [[property tax]] credits even after moving.<ref name=\"approves\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Committee approves King's tax proposal |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/search/content/news/stories/2008/04/02/040308_4b_tax_question.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=2 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-04 }}</ref> In total, King sponsored 12 House and Senate bills, seven of which were passed into law.<ref name=\"largely\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Lawmakers largely successful with bills |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/06/14/061508_8b_Bill_report.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=14 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-19 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the legislative session, King was named to an interim committee focusing on wildfire and development issues in mountain areas of Colorado.<ref name=\"forestcmte\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=King appointed to forest committee |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/06/11/061208_6b_King_appointment.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=11 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-14 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In October, King called for a legislative audit on enforcement of a state law prohibiting [[sanctuary city]] policies.<ref name=\"auditimm\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Montero |title=State Rep. King wants immigration law audited |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/oct/14/state-rep-king-wants-immigration-law-audited/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}</ref><ref name=\"wantsaud\">{{cite news|first=Gary |last=Harmon |title=King wants state review of compliance with law against immigration sanctuary |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/10/12/101108_3A_King_immigration.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=12 October 2008 |access-date=2008-11-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016121634/http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/10/12/101108_3A_King_immigration.html |archive-date=October 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, King, frustrated with new regulation and with comments made regarding job losses in Colorado's energy industry, called for Gov. Ritter to fire Dave Neslin, the director of the Colorado Oil and Gas Conservation Commission.<ref name=\"replace\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=King asks for replacement of CO |url=http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20081216/COMMUNITY_NEWS/812159977/1006/NONE&parentprofile=1059&title=King%20asks%20for%20replacement%20of%20COGCC%20director |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=16 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"urges\">{{cite news |first=Todd |last=Hartman |title=Lawmaker urges firing of oil, gas conservation official |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/dec/16/lawmaker-urges-firing-of-oil-gas-conservation/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=16 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 election===\nRep. King sought re-election to the Colorado legislature in 2008; he faced no opposition for the Republican nomination<ref name=\"intensify\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=As races intensify, candidates reveal campaign funds |url=http://gjfreepress.com/article/20080428/COMMUNITY_NEWS/448570948 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=28 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-29 }}</ref> and ran unopposed in the general election as well.<ref name=\"noopp\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Saccone  |title=Rep. King to face no opponent at polls |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/stories/2008/06/12/061308_Candidate.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=12 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-14 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"finance\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson  |title=Campaign finance update |url=http://gjfreepress.com/article/20080613/COMMUNITY_NEWS/404419289 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-14 }}</ref>\n\nKing named education and energy issues as his priorities for the next legislative session.<ref name=\"kidsvot\">{{cite news |first=Erin |last=Slilekoks |title=Kids Voting, Oct. 13, 2008 |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/hp/content/news/opinion/stories/2008/10/12/101308_14A_kids_voting.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=12 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In contrast to his typical opposition to tax increases, King also supported a local school bond measure in Grand Junction that was on the 2008 ballot.<ref name=\"penry\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Penry, King endorse School District 51 bond issue |url=http://www.gjfreepress.com/article/20080911/COMMUNITY_NEWS/809109933/1064&parentprofile=-1 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=11 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-10-30 }}</ref>\n\n===2009 legislative session===\nFor the 2009 legislative session, King was appointed to the House Judiciary Committee and the House Transportation and Energy Committee.<ref name=\"cmte09\">\n{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 |access-date=30 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231125753/http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node%2F92 |archive-date=31 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2009, King continued his active engagement in the legislature by serving as primary sponsor for 13 bills. His major focus included legislation with an emerging focus on increasing government accountability and transparency. In particular, he sponsored two measures: SB09-241 and HB09-1180. SB09-241<ref name=\"SB09241\">{{cite news | title=SB09-241 |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A33C46D1F9F4F2EC87257553007F530D?Open&file=241_enr.pdf|accessdate=10 October 2012 }}</ref>\n(Katie's Law) requires DNA sampling upon arrest for felony offenses, to be expunged if no conviction is obtained, and Rep. King received national recognition when he was awarded the \"Katie's Heroes\" award for his role in passing this legislation. HB09-1180<ref name=\"HB09-1180\">{{cite news |title=HB09-1180 |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/0CCEBB17C7B80D548725753800635131?Open&file=1180_enr.pdf | accessdate=10 Oct 2012 }}</ref> would have provided more Second Amendment personal safety options for Colorado concealed carry permit holders, but it was postponed indefinitely in committee.\n\n===2010 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=King\n|Year=2010\n|Bill Number 1=HB10-1054\n|Bill Number 2=HB10-1136\n|Bill Number 3= HB10-1334\n|Bill Number 4= SB10-079\n|Bill Number 5= SB10-092\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/C93F548942F35723872576A8002A2A41?Open&file=1054_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/E1BF145053E3EA62872576AC00651D78?Open&file=1136_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/6497F94EFEE7652F872576B80066D97B?Open&file=1334_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/2EA9C2A5C1FE6C11872576AA00696FD4?Open&file=079_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2010a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/2D5FE3C68F88F2DC872576A80027B78E?Open&file=092_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 4= Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning presenting school safety information at institutions of higher education.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning emergency safety procedures in Kindergarten-through-twelfth-grade schools.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning changes to indecency crimes. \n|Bill Title 4= Concerning authority to offer additional programs at Mesa State College.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning the exemption from federal regulation of certain items related to exercising the right to bear arms.\n}}\nIn 2010, King presented a bill that would have required all schools, kindergarten\u2013twelfth grade, to perform emergency safety drills each academic year, in addition to the normal fire evacuation drills. The emergency safety protocol drills would include lockdown, evacuation and reverse-evacuation, and [[shelter in place]] drills. However, HB10-1136 was assigned to the House Education Committee, where it was postponed indefinitely.\n\n==Colorado Senate 2011-2015==\n\n===2010 Election===\nIn 2010, Rep. King was eligible for re-election to the 54th House seat; however, he instead chose to run for the open Senate seat in District 7. In the general November election, he defeated Democrat [[Claudette Konola]] and Libertarian [[Gilbert Fuller]] with 67% of the vote.<ref name=\"2010 Results\">{{cite news |title=Colorado State Senate Election Results 2012 |url= http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-senate/2010/\n|work=Denver Post |accessdate=10 Oct 2012 }}\n</ref>\n\n===2011 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=King\n|Year=2011\n|Bill Number 1=SB11-027\n|Bill Number 2=SB11-046\n|Bill Number 3=SB11-093\n|Bill Number 4=SB11-098\n|Bill Number 5=SB11-173\n|Bill Number 6=HB11-1080\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/591FE603A91DC2458725780800800F35?Open&file=027_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/894CDD0D7A3C8DF28725780800803B37?Open&file=046_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D186918CCBB6915287257822007BD8FE?Open&file=093_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/709BABFEFC8F2BC68725781C00698989?Open&file=098_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/85763B644B0DC1F68725780800800F8A?Open&file=173_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2011a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9820262AD8F68ED08725780800804995?Open&file=1080_enr.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 3=Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Status 5= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 6= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning the Colorado economic stability fund.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning the mandatory post-enactment review by legislative service agencies of the implementation of enacted bills.\n|Bill Title 3= Concerning the continuation of the interagency task force on drunk driving.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning the phase-out of the property tax on business personal property.\n|Bill Title 5= Concerning interoperable communications in schools.\n|Bill Title 6= Concerning the address confidentiality program, and making an appropriation therefor.\n}}\nFor the 2011 legislative session, Senator King focused on a bill that would have phased-out the property tax on business personal property. SB11-098 allowed for future enactment, once the state has reached prosperity levels adequate to deal with the decrease of tax income. The bill was assigned to the Senate State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee, and it was postponed indefinitely on a party-line 3-2 vote.<ref name=\"Open States SB11-098\">{{cite news |title=Open States \u2013 SB11-098|url= http://openstates.org/co/bills/2011A/SB11-098/|\nwork=Open States |accessdate=11 Oct 2012 }}</ref>\n\nKing was appointed to serve on the Senate Transportation, Judiciary, and Legislative Audit Committees for the 68th General Assembly.<ref name=\"CO GA Page\">{{cite news|title=Colorado General Assembly-Steve King|url=http://www.state.co.us/gov_dir/leg_dir/Senate/members/Sen07.htm|work=Colorado General Assembly|access-date=10 Oct 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022153333/http://www.state.co.us/gov_dir/leg_dir/Senate/members/Sen07.htm|archive-date=22 October 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\nSenator King was appointed to the Mental Illness in the Criminal Justice System Interim Committee for the 2011 Interim; this committee focused on maintaining legislative oversight into the continuing examination of persons who are mentally ill in the Colorado Justice System.\nKing was appointed to the Police Officers' and Firefighters' Pension Reform Commission and the Senate Transportation Legislation Review Committee for the 2011 Interim as well.\n\n===2012 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=King\n|Year=2012\n|Bill Number 1=SB12-034\n|Bill Number 2=SB12-079\n|Bill Number 3=SB12-117\n|Bill Number 4=HB12-1004\n|Bill Number 5=HB12-1064\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/493E5830AD3300A487257981007F0D10?Open&file=034_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/F05828BE5B756CE987257981007F34AC?Open&file=079_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/3830B379C5DC1E8487257982007166A1?Open&file=117_ren.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/210803A9B1165F8B87257981007F6946?Open&file=1004_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2012a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/E02212357C1248D187257981007F40BA?Open&file=1064_ren.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 2= Signed by Gov. [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely on House calendar\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 5=Postponed indefinitely in Senate committee\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning repeal of the rapid screen program to identify high-emitting motor vehicles.\n|Bill Title 2= Concerning revisions to the Safe2Tell Program relating to advances in communications technology.\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the penalties for person who drive while under the influence of alcohol or drugs.\n|Bill Title 4= Concerning requiring local building codes to allow the use of lumber milled from certain trees as building framing material.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning the prohibition of limitations concerning firearms during an official state of emergency. \n}}\nIn 2012, King focused on addressing a number of important issues in Colorado: addressing technological changes for the Safe2Tell program, updating penalties for impaired driving, and focusing on correcting gun limitation laws.<ref name=\"CO Capitol Watch\">{{cite news |title=Colorado General Assembly-Steve King |url=http://www.coloradocapitolwatch.com/bill/1/HB12-1064/2012/0/ |work=Colorado Capitol Watch |accessdate=11 Oct 2012 }}</ref> HB12-1064 would prohibit government and law enforcement from banning possession and use of firearms during a state emergency unless that weapon was being used for a crime. The bill, one of four gun bills proposed during session, passed on a party-line vote in the Republican-controlled House before being sent over to the Democrat-controlled Senate. In the Senate, it was introduced to the Senate State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee and failed to be referred to the Committee of the Whole on a 2-3 party-line vote. \n<ref name=\"Open States HB12-0164\">{{cite news |title=Colorado General Assembly-Steve King|url= http://openstates.org/co/bills/2012A/HB12-1064/|\nwork=Open States |accessdate=11 Oct 2012 }}</ref>\n\nKing maintained his appointments on two Interim Committees for the 2012 off-session as well: the Police Officers' and Firefighters' Pension Reform Commission and the Senate Transportation Legislation Review Committee.\n\n===2013 Legislative Session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Senator\n|Name=King\n|Year=2013\n|Bill Number 1=\n|Bill Number 2=\n|Bill Number 3=\n|Bill Number 4=\n|Bill Number 5=\n|Bill Link 1=\n|Bill Link 2=\n|Bill Link 3=\n|Bill Link 4=\n|Bill Link 5=\n|Bill Status 1=\n|Bill Status 2=\n|Bill Status 3=\n|Bill Status 4=\n|Bill Status 5=\n|Bill Title 1=\n|Bill Title 2= \n|Bill Title 3=\n|Bill Title 4= \n|Bill Title 5= \n}}\n\n\tKing was appointed to serve on the Senate Judiciary Committee, Transportation Committee, and the Legislative Audit Committee.\n\n==Run for sheriff and criminal indictment and plea==\nOn June 6, 2014, King was accused by Mesa County Sheriff Stan Hilkey of falsifying timecards King had filed in association with his part-time job with the department. At the time, King was running to replace Hilkey as sheriff, and denied all allegations and initially refused to drop from the race. On July 16, King announced he would be withdrawing from the race due to the impending allegations.<ref>http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_26246364/state-sen-steve-king-charged-three-felonies?source=pkg</ref> On January 23, 2015, King pleaded guilty to embezzlement and official misconduct. He was ordered to pay restitution and serve 2 years probation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/former-colorado-state-senator-steve-king-pleads-guilty-to-embezzlement01232015 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192012/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/former-colorado-state-senator-steve-king-pleads-guilty-to-embezzlement01232015 |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/steve-king-cops-a-plea|title=Steve King cops a plea  {{!}}  GJSentinel.com|last=Shockley|first=Paul|website=www.gjsentinel.com|access-date=2016-05-18|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602032330/http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/steve-king-cops-a-plea|archive-date=2016-06-02|df=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140208023159/http://www.votesteveking.com/ Campaign web site]\n*[http://www.coloradosenatenews.com/?q=content/senator-steve-king Colorado GOP Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121022153333/http://www.state.co.us/gov_dir/leg_dir/Senate/members/Sen07.htm Colorado General Assembly Website]\n\n{{Colorado State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Steve}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Colorado politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n", "name_user": "Johnsagent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRun for sheriff and criminal indictment and plea:date locator", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_King_(Colorado_legislator)"}
